<section xml:id="exponentials-and-logarithms">
<title>Exponentials and logarithms</title>


<paragraphs xml:id="the-plan-4">
<title>The Plan</title>

<p> Logarithmic and exponential functions, while often
intimidating, appear throughout microbiology, chemistry, statistics, and
mathematics. We will understand the basic computational and graphical
properties of these functions and their connection to applications.
</p>

<p> A population of size <m>N</m> loses a factor of
approximately <m>\underline{\hspace{2cm}}</m> of its genetic variability
each generation. Consider a population of <m>N=20</m> individuals that
<term>loses</term> a factor of  each generation.<!-- linebreak -->A
population <term>maintains</term> a factor of
<m>\underline{\hspace{2cm}}</m> of its variability each generation. How
much variability is left after 5 generations?
</p>

