<theorem xml:id="thm-properties-powers">
<title>Properties of exponents</title>
<statement>
<p>Consider the following laws for for real numbers
<m>a</m>, <m>m</m>, and <m>n</m>.

<ol>
<li> <p> <m>a^{m}\cdot a^{n} = a^{m+n}</m></p> </li>
<li> <p> <m>(a^n)^m = a^{nm}</m></p> </li>
<li> <p> <m>a^{-n} = \frac{1}{a^{n}}</m></p> </li>
<li> <p> <m>\frac{a^n}{a^m} = a^{n-m}</m></p> </li>
<li> <p> <m>a^1 = a</m></p> </li>
<li> <p> <m>a^0 = 1</m></p> </li>
</ol></p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<p> Common bases in science are
<ul>
<li> <p> <m>10</m> throughout science and nature</p> </li>
<li> <p> <m>e</m> throughout science</p> </li>
<li> <p> <m>2</m> throughout computer science</p> </li>
</ul></p>

<p> Though we think of exponents as <sq>multiplying
<m>a</m>’s together</sq> certain instance only make sense if we use the
above laws. How can we multiply factors of <m>2</m> together <m>(-3)</m>
times?
</p>

